translated_by_TA:
I was leaving, my fists in my burst pockets;
my overcoat too was becoming ideal;
I was walking under the sky, muse! and I was your faithful one;
oh! there! there! what splendid loves I dreamed of!
my only breeches had a large hole.
—a dreamy little thumb, I rattled off rhymes as I ran. My inn was at the Big Dipper.
—my stars in the sky had a gentle rustle
and I listened to them, sitting by the roadside,
those pleasant September evenings when I felt drops
of dew on my forehead, like a wine of vigor;
where, rhyming amidst fantastic shadows,
like lyres, I pulled the elastics
of my wounded shoes, one foot close to my heart!
